The heat pump industry is booming, with demand exceeding supply - indeed, we have had 
the perfect conditions for the sector, thanks to high gas prices and cut-off of Russian gas 
supplies, plus high subsidies from governments. 
However, as we explore in this note, we believe current price levels of heat pumps are only 
sustainable with significant subsidy, which will not be sustainable as installation numbers 
increase - indeed, at German levels of subsidy, heat pump subsidies per year would cost 
0.5% of total EU government expenditure, about 10% of the annual EU defence budget. 
Current plans to completely ban fossil fuel installations in Germany from January 2024 
also appear unrealistic to us. 
Payback time against gas boilers can be nearly 20 years without subsidy and this will need 
to fall to drive mass adoption. Asian manufacturers such as LG and Samsung (both No 
Current Recommendation - NCR) have been gaining market share with cheaper products, 
and there are also capacity additions from European manufacturers. 
Thus we believe pricing will come down, putting pressure on both revenue growth and, 
more importantly, margins in the medium term - which are at --15% and can fall to single 
digits. It is in H2'23 and FY'24 that we expect to see the first signs of such pricing pressure 
affecting NIBE's revenues. 
We reiterate our Short recommendation, with N60% downside potential, although bring up 
our price target slightly to SEK 42 per share to account for continued strong company 
performance and thus an increase to our FY'23 and FY'24 earnings estimates. 
Germany - Heat Pump Economics 
In Germany, the drive away from natural gas to renewables is higher than almost anywhere 
due to the particularly high previous usage of Russian natural gas. The German

local cl_fov_enabled = CreateClientConVar("cl_fov_enabled", 1, true, false, "Enable custom FOV?")
local running = false

local function CalcView(ply, pos, angles, fov, ...)
    if running or ply:GetVehicle():GetThirdPersonMode() or IsValid(ply:GetObserverTarget()) or (IsValid(ply:GetActiveWeapon()) and ply:GetActiveWeapon():GetClass() == "gmod_camera") then

    end

    running = true

    local t = hook.Run("CalcView", ply, pos, angles, newFOV, ...) or { origin = pos, fov = newFOV }

    running = false

    return t
end

local function ToggleFOVRemap()
    if cl_fov_enabled:GetBool() then
        hook.Add("CalcView", "FOVRemap.CalcView", CalcView)
    else
        hook.Remove("CalcView", "FOVRemap.CalcView")

end

Radiation-induced myocardial fibrosis (RIMF) is a potentially severe lethal clinical complication after chest radiotherapy (RT), which is the major common denominator of radiation-induced heart disease (RIHD). RIMF is characterized by decreased ventricular elasticity and distensibility, resulting in decreased ejection fraction and heart failure, and even sudden cardiac death, which impairs the long-term health of post-RT survivors and limits dose and intensity of RT required to effectively kill tumor cells. Although the exact mechanisms involving in RIMF are not clear, overwhelming evidence indicates that the occurrence of RIMF is related to various cells, regulatory molecules, and cytokines. And accurately diagnosing and identifying patients who may progress to RIMF is challenging. Despite the urgent need for an effective treatment, there is no medical therapy for RIMF approved for routine clinical application. In this review, we have focused on the underlying pathophysiology that is critically involved in the initiation and progression of RIMF and then outlined potential preventative and therapeutic strategies to counter this toxicity, providing a basis for therapeutic strategies of RIMF.

data: Keeping a personal history provides major benefits for both yourself and future generations, but many people believe it’s either too embarrassing, too time-consuming, or too overwhelming to create an honest, thorough record of their daily life. The truth is that there are a variety of ways you can use to document your life, and none of them have to complicate it. Here are thirteen easy ways to document your life so that you—and your grandkids—can celebrate your joyful life by remembering it.

1
Keep a Journal
Keeping a journal is my go-to choice for documenting my life. I got my first journal as a present from my parents on my 9th birthday, and I just started journal #73 about a week ago. I’m grateful that my mom and dad helped me set a pattern of writing early on, because I love reading back through my old journals to reminisce. It’s amazing how many events and people would be gone from my life forever if I hadn’t kept a journal.

If you find the prospect of keeping a daily journal daunting, keeping a weekly or monthly journal works, too. Just make sure you set aside a specific time to write, or it’ll never happen. If I know I’m not going to be able to write for a few days, I’ll also keep a running list of things I want to make sure I remember to write about.

2
One Sentence a Day
If you don’t feel like you can write about your day in detail, don’t despair. Even writing a single sentence every day can give future generations a glimpse into your life, and you might find that it inspires you to write more.

Background: Following is some material on advanced design patterns in RESTful API and microservice architecture:
- Idempotency key: sometimes we want to ensure certain actions are performed at most once. The idempotency key pattern implement this by having the client supply a client-generated key and add it as part of their request. Server side should ensure that subsequent repeated requests with the same idempotency key is ignored or that its effect is idempotent - that doing the action twice or more is the same as doing it just once.
- Other metadata: a RESTful API endpoint could allow the client to add its own metadata object in the request, with arbitrary json data allowed as long as its top level is an object.
- Controller resource: A common question in REST is how can complex transaction be modelled if REST is mostly like plain CRUD on data. One pattern to solve for this is to explicitly model such a transaction/operation as an abstract object itself, with lifecycle controlled/triggered by doing RESTful operation on this resources.
- Distributed Saga and Compensating transaction: on the backend, a business transaction may correspond to multiple DB transaction, and potentially involve external/3rd party API calls. These are all actions that fundamentally cannot be made ACID. These pattern solve this problem by using an alternative model where each step is made idempotent, with explicit procedure to compensate for the effect through a separate action in the event the whole business transaction is considered to have failed and need to be "rollbacked" (note the quote because it is not rollback in the conventional sense).

Suggest possible advanced scenario where these patterns may be used to provide a good solution.

The cherries are fermented as they pass through a civet's intestines, and after being defecated with other fecal matter, they are collected.[1] Asian palm civets are increasingly caught in the wild and traded for this purpose.

Kopi luwak is produced mainly on the Indonesian islands of Sumatra, Java, Bali, Sulawesi, and in East Timor. It is also widely gathered in the forest or produced in farms in the islands of the Philippines,[3] where the product is called kape motit in the Cordillera region, kapé alamíd in Tagalog areas, kapé melô or kapé musang in Mindanao, and kahawa kubing in the Sulu Archipelago. 'NAME_1 coffee' is a loose English translation of its Vietnamese name cà phê Chồn.

Producers of the coffee beans argue that the process may improve coffee through two mechanisms: selection, where civets choose to eat only certain cherries; and digestion, where biological or chemical mechanisms in the animals' digestive tracts alter the composition of the coffee cherries.

The traditional method of collecting feces from wild Asian palm civets has given way to an intensive farming method, in which the palm civets are kept in battery cages and are force-fed the cherries. This method of production has raised ethical concerns about the treatment of civets and the conditions they are made to live in, which include isolation, poor diet, small cages, and a high mortality rate.

Although kopi luwak is a form of processing rather than a variety of coffee, it has been called one of the most expensive coffees in the world, with retail prices reaching US$100 per kilogram for farmed beans and US$1,300 per kilogram for wild-collected beans.[7] Another epithet given to it is that it is NAME_2 of coffees.

Descriptive analytics, as defined by the online HBS blog (2021), is a powerful analytical approach that focuses on elucidating the factors that led to a particular outcome. It involves analyzing historical and current data to gain insights into trends and patterns related to the specific outcome under investigation. This statistical method enables decision-makers to comprehensively understand how the business has evolved over time by examining a wide range of past data and comparing it to established benchmarks.
In the context of the case study on Coca-Cola European Partners (CCE), descriptive analytics plays a pivotal role in shedding light on the organization's HR transformation journey. By leveraging historical and real-time data, CCE's centralized HR reporting and analytics team gained a deeper understanding of their HR performance and the impact of their initiatives. Through careful analysis and interpretation of various data sources, including internal databases, financial reports, and customer feedback, CCE was able to uncover meaningful patterns and relationships.
Descriptive analytics offers a means to summarize and interpret the collected data, thereby identifying key performance indicators (KPIs), tracking progress toward business objectives, and pinpointing areas for improvement. By harnessing this analytical approach, CCE could effectively measure the impact of their HR practices, assess their alignment with organizational goals, and drive data-informed decision-making. This comprehensive analysis of historical data provided CCE with a solid foundation for their HR analytics program and allowed them to make informed strategic choices to optimize HR performance.
To conduct descriptive analytics, businesses need to gather and organize relevant data from diverse sources, ensuring a comprehensive representation of the factors influencing the outcome. Through the application of statistical techniques and data visualizations, such as histograms, scatter plots, and heat maps, businesses can effectively analyse the data, identify trends and patterns, and communicate their findings to stakeholders. In the case of CCE, these visualizations played a vital role in conveying the insights gained from descriptive analytics to the leadership team, enabling them to grasp complex information more easily and make informed decisions regarding HR practices.

Some important concepts covered in their book are listed here: 
• There are two kinds of technology markets: Gorilla Games and Royalty Markets.  In a Gorilla Game, the players are dubbed gorillas and chimps. In a Royalty Market,  the participants are kings, princes, and serfs. 
• Gorilla Games exist because the market leaders possess proprietary technology that  makes it difficult for competitors to compete. This proprietary technology creates  a moat that can be difficult to overcome. 
• In Royalty Markets, the technology has been commoditized and standardized. In  a Royalty Market, it's difficult to become a leader and it's easy to fall off the number  one position.  
• The more proprietary features a gorilla creates in their product and the bigger the  moat they establish, the more difficult and expensive it becomes to switch to  a competitor and the stronger the gorilla becomes. 
• This creates a virtuous cycle for the market leader or gorilla

Esta pode ser implementada em qualquer tipo de organização, com ou sem fins lucrativos, privada ou pública, pequena ou grande, e é escrita pelos melhores especialistas mundiais no campo de segurança da informação e prové metodologia para a implementação da gestão da segurança da informação em uma organização. Ela também possibilita que organizações obtenham certificação, o que significa que um organismo certificador independente confirmou que uma organização implementou a segurança da informação em conformidade com a ISO 27001. Segundo esta ISO, o domínio Classificação de Ativos da Informação Intangíveis, apresenta papéis importantes para uma boa definição do processo de classificação, da rotulação e do tratamento da informação. Por meio desses papéis é possivel identificar quem estará envolvido no ciclo de vida da informação. The contents of the nutrients were analyzed after digestion using a simulated dynamic digestion model, and the effects of different processing conditions, i.e., low-temperature processing and storage (25 °C) and high-temperature cooking (100 °C), of seal meat were investigated. Hydrolysates with antioxidant activity decreased the amounts of the less desirable Fe3+ ions in the seal meat digests. After treatment with hydrolysates at room temperature, a much higher total Fe content of 781.99 mg/kg was observed compared to other treatment conditions. The release of amino acids increased with temperature and was 520.54 mg/g for the hydrolysate-treated sample versus 413.12 mg/g for the control seal meat sample treated in buffer. Overall, this study provides useful data on the potential use of seal meat as a food product with high nutritive value and seal meat hydrolysates with antioxidant activity as preservatives to control oxidation in food.

data: Keeping a personal history provides major benefits for both yourself and future generations, but many people believe it’s either too embarrassing, too time-consuming, or too overwhelming to create an honest, thorough record of their daily life. The truth is that there are a variety of ways you can use to document your life, and none of them have to complicate it. Here are thirteen easy ways to document your life so that you—and your grandkids—can celebrate your joyful life by remembering it.

1
Keep a Journal
Keeping a journal is my go-to choice for documenting my life. I got my first journal as a present from my parents on my 9th birthday, and I just started journal #73 about a week ago. I’m grateful that my mom and dad helped me set a pattern of writing early on, because I love reading back through my old journals to reminisce. It’s amazing how many events and people would be gone from my life forever if I hadn’t kept a journal.

If you find the prospect of keeping a daily journal daunting, keeping a weekly or monthly journal works, too. Just make sure you set aside a specific time to write, or it’ll never happen. If I know I’m not going to be able to write for a few days, I’ll also keep a running list of things I want to make sure I remember to write about.

2
One Sentence a Day
If you don’t feel like you can write about your day in detail, don’t despair. Even writing a single sentence every day can give future generations a glimpse into your life, and you might find that it inspires you to write more.

Background: Following is some material on advanced design patterns in RESTful API and microservice architecture:
- Idempotency key: sometimes we want to ensure certain actions are performed at most once. The idempotency key pattern implement this by having the client supply a client-generated key and add it as part of their request. Server side should ensure that subsequent repeated requests with the same idempotency key is ignored or that its effect is idempotent - that doing the action twice or more is the same as doing it just once.
- Other metadata: a RESTful API endpoint could allow the client to add its own metadata object in the request, with arbitrary json data allowed as long as its top level is an object.
- Controller resource: A common question in REST is how can complex transaction be modelled if REST is mostly like plain CRUD on data. One pattern to solve for this is to explicitly model such a transaction/operation as an abstract object itself, with lifecycle controlled/triggered by doing RESTful operation on this resources.
- Distributed Saga and Compensating transaction: on the backend, a business transaction may correspond to multiple DB transaction, and potentially involve external/3rd party API calls. These are all actions that fundamentally cannot be made ACID. These pattern solve this problem by using an alternative model where each step is made idempotent, with explicit procedure to compensate for the effect through a separate action in the event the whole business transaction is considered to have failed and need to be "rollbacked" (note the quote because it is not rollback in the conventional sense).

Suggest possible advanced scenario where these patterns may be used to provide a good solution.

Planning For Answer: The field Q(sqrt(2), sqrt(3), sqrt(18)) is an extension field of Q that includes the square roots of 2, 3, and 18. Notice that sqrt(18) = sqrt(2*9) = sqrt(2)sqrt(9) = 3sqrt(2), so sqrt(18) can be expressed in terms of sqrt(2), which means that including sqrt(18) in the field doesn't actually increase the degree of the extension.
Thus, the field Q(sqrt(2), sqrt(3), sqrt(18)) is the same as the field Q(sqrt(2), sqrt(3)).
For the degree of a simple extension field Q(a, b) over Q, we want to find the least common multiple (lcm) of the degrees of the extension fields Q(a) over Q and Q(b) over Q.
sqrt(2) and sqrt(3) are both irrational numbers, and the minimal polynomials that they are roots of are both quadratic (x^2 - 2 and x^2 - 3, respectively). Thus, the extension fields Q(sqrt(2)) and Q(sqrt(3)) are both of degree 2 over Q.
Therefore, the field Q(sqrt(2), sqrt(3)) has degree lcm(2, 2) = 2 * 2 = 4 over Q. The square root of 18 does not increase the degree of the field, as explained above.
So, the field Q(sqrt(2), sqrt(3), sqrt(18)) also has degree 4 over Q.

And why don't all bodies stay in this condition? The answers to these questions live six feet underground. And perhaps the soil’s most important inhabitants are microbes, organisms no larger than several hundred nanometers that decompose all the planet’s dead and dying organic material. Imagine we drop an apple in the forest. As soon as it contacts the soil, worms and other invertebrates begin breaking it down into smaller parts; absorbing nutrients from what they consume and excreting the rest. This first stage of decomposition sets the scene for microbes. The specific microbes present depend on the environment. For example, in grasslands and farm fields there tend to be more bacteria, which excel at breaking down grass and leaves. But in this temperate forest there are more fungi, capable of breaking down complex woody materials. However, as we explore in this note, we believe current price levels of heat pumps are only 
sustainable with significant subsidy, which will not be sustainable as installation numbers 
increase - indeed, at German levels of subsidy, heat pump subsidies per year would cost 
0.5% of total EU government expenditure, about 10% of the annual EU defence budget. 
Current plans to completely ban fossil fuel installations in Germany from January 2024 
also appear unrealistic to us. 
Payback time against gas boilers can be nearly 20 years without subsidy and this will need 
to fall to drive mass adoption. Asian manufacturers such as LG and Samsung (both No 
Current Recommendation - NCR) have been gaining market share with cheaper products, 
and there are also capacity additions from European manufacturers. 
Thus we believe pricing will come down, putting pressure on both revenue growth and, 
more importantly, margins in the medium term - which are at --15% and can fall to single 
digits. It is in H2'23 and FY'24 that we expect to see the first signs of such pricing pressure 
affecting NIBE's revenues. 
We reiterate our Short recommendation, with N60% downside potential, although bring up 
our price target slightly to SEK 42 per share to account for continued strong company 
performance and thus an increase to our FY'23 and FY'24 earnings estimates. 
Germany - Heat Pump Economics 
In Germany, the drive away from natural gas to renewables is higher than almost anywhere 
due to the particularly high previous usage of Russian natural gas. The German 
government has banned new fossil-fuel heating installations unless they are part of a 
system that runs on >65% renewables, starting in January 2024. 
We look at the payback time for a customer when installing a heat pump compared to a 
new gas boiler in Germany to see if the economics stack up both for German households 
and the government. We have seen various payback periods mentioned, and therefore 
attempt to come up with our own estimate of the payback time for an air source heat 
pump that can power heating and hot water in a typical single-family house, which is 
150sqm and uses 24,000 kWh of gas per year for heating and hot water.
